default7. defaultRole modelsdefault7.1 
defaultMuch has been made of the use of successful female scientists as role models for the purpose of attracting and retaining greater numbers of women in STEM. 
defaultSame-sex role models or ambassadors in STEM are advocated for their contribution in
default rescuing,
default rehabilitating and mobilising the mind-sets of those contemplating STEM subject choices/careers governed by misassumptions regards to their suitability for a STEM
default career, purely on the grounds of gender. 
defaultSenior STEM role models offer evidence that women can achieve real success in STEM contexts and rise to positions of authority and high office. The effectiveness of senior role models may also however be potentiall
defaulty compromised by a lack of 
defaultaspirational
default-proximity or in other words a sense that their achievements, when contextualized amidst the paucity of their numbers, appear even more exceptional, out-of-reach or through the more sceptical lens, 
defaultserendipitous
default. In t
defaulthis context, senior role models whilst offering ‘proof-of-concept’ also demonstrate the arduousness of the STEM career for women, and a sense that even limited success will be hard-fought – and not according to principles of meritocracy or 
defaulta 
defaultlevel playing 
defaultfield of opportunity between the sexes.
